# Ruby Basics â€“ Concepts & Examples

This file explains basic Ruby concepts with simple examples.
These fundamentals are widely used in Ruby on Rails applications.

---

## String Object ID & Immutability

- Strings are objects in Ruby
- Modifying a string creates a new object

```ruby
name = "Manu"
puts name.object_id

name = name + "MR"
puts name.object_id
```

---

## Data Types in Ruby

```ruby
a = 10          # Integer
b = true        # Boolean
c = 10.5        # Float
d = [1,2,3]     # Array
e = { name: "Manu", age: 24 }  # Hash
```

Use `.class` to identify the data type.

---

## User Input

```ruby
puts "Enter your name:"
name = gets.chomp
puts "Hello, #{name}"
```

- `gets` reads input
- `chomp` removes newline

---

## Class & Object

```ruby
class Student
  attr_accessor :name, :age

  def display
    puts "Name: #{name}, Age: #{age}"
  end
end
```

---

## Creating Objects

```ruby
student = Student.new
student.name = "Manu"
student.age = 21
student.display
```

---

## Multiple Objects Using Array

```ruby
students = []

3.times do
  s = Student.new
  s.name = "Ramu"
  s.age = 12
  students << s
end

students.each(&:display)
```

---

## Variables & Comments

```ruby
name = "Rahul"
id = 125
flag = true
```

Comments start with `#`.

---

## String Interpolation & Casting

```ruby
num = 100
puts "#{name} id : #{num}"
puts name + num.to_s
```

---

## Methods

```ruby
def multiply(a, b)
  a * b
end
```

---

## Array Input

```ruby
arr = []
5.times do
  arr << gets.chomp.to_i
end
```

---

## Symbols

```ruby
sym = :name
puts sym.class
```

---

## Summary

- Everything in Ruby is an object
- Strings are immutable
- Classes and objects form the foundation

